Kenya and the United States have launched the Inaugural Bilateral Strategic Dialogue to anchor their relationship. The launch was signed by Foreign Affairs Cabinet secretary Monica Juma and US Deputy Secretary John Sullivan  in Washington DC. Sullivan said the framework will cover four pillars; economic prosperity trade and investment, defence cooperation democracy governance and civilians’ security multilateral and regional issues.  “We are launching a new stage of our relations with one of our key friends in Africa and the world,” he said. Juma said the meeting is an indication of strategic vision of the two presidents. “When we were coming for this meeting, President Uhuru directed us to understand the importance and the meaning of this dialogue which must work towards benefiting our peoples and we must work together,” she said.